did.abstract: The papers consist of correspondence, hospital consultation files, reports, subject files, writings, research material, audiocassettes, and photographs, which document Albert W. Snoke's career in hospital administration and his interest in health care. The papers also include material concerning the career of his wife, Parnie Storey Hamilton Snoke, and the Snoke, Storey, and Hamilton families. The papers form part of the Contemporary Medical Care and Health Policy Collection. Albert Waldo Snoke was born in Fort Steilacoom, Washington, in 1907. After receiving a B.S. degree from the University of Washington in 1928, he attended Stanford University Medical School and received his M.D. degree in 1933. In 1936, Snoke joined the staff of the Strong Memorial Hospital, Rochester, New York, and became its assistant director in 1937. Snoke left Rochester in 1946 to assume the directorship of Grace-New Haven Hospital in New Haven, Connecticut. In New Haven he also taught hospital administration at Yale University and oversaw the development of the Yale-New Haven Hospital, serving as its executive director from 1965-1968. From 1969-1973, Snoke worked in Illinois as coordinator of health services and later as acting executive director of the Illinois Comprehensive State Health Planning Agency. In 1987 his book, Hospitals, Health, and People , was published. Snoke died on April 18, 1988.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Albert Snoke Papers document the professional life of a hospital administrator known for his contributions to improved patient care. The papers will be of interest to those studying the history of hospital administration, the development of health care delivery systems, and the growth of community hospitals into research centers affiliated with schools of medicine. Though the files contain references to Snoke's work as executive director of Grace-New Haven Hospital, the vast majority of the records of this period are found in the records of Yale-New Haven Hospital (MS 835) in Manuscripts and Archives. These records also contain Snoke's retrospective notes, in which he explains issues and events documented in the executive director's files in MS 835. Snoke created the notes when contemplating writing a history of the hospital and also in anticipation of transferring his papers to Manuscripts and Archives. He may also have used them in preparing for the oral history interview he gave in 1987 (Series II, folders 184-185).

The Snoke Papers focus on Snoke's participation in professional organizations and his role as a consultant, advisor, and author. They also contain personal papers of Albert Snoke, which document his early interests in scouting and the outdoors, particularly Mount Rainier in Washington. Papers of other members of the Snoke and Storey families are also in these files. They focus on life at Stanford University and in Palo Alto, California, but also include a Civil War diary of Riley Storey.

The diary is the oldest item in the papers; other memorabilia of Thomas and Parnie Storey also dates from the nineteenth century. The bulk of the papers, however, dates from 1946, when Snoke moved from Rochester, New York to New Haven. The papers, which include correspondence, hospital consultation files, reports, subject files, writings, research material, and photographs, are arranged in five series, by record type: General Files, Writings, Topical Files, Personal and Family Papers, and Photographs. Thus material on a particular subject might be found in several series. For instance, those interested in Snoke's years in Illinois would need to look in the General Files for correspondence with and memoranda to Illinois Governor Richard Ogilivie, but they might also look for articles and reports from this period in Writings, background material and notes in Topical Files, and pictorial material in Photographs. The inventory of folder titles includes cross-references which are extensive but not all-inclusive. Unless the cross-reference includes a series number, the citation is to a folder number within the same series.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: Albert Waldo Snoke was born in Fort Steilacoom, Washington, on July 19, 1907. Snoke was active in Boy Scouts and attained the rank of Eagle. In 1924 he was part of the United States troop which participated in an international jamboree in Copenhagen, Denmark. After graduating from Puyallup High School, he attended the University of Washington and received a B.S. degree in 1928. Snoke then went to the Stanford University Medical School, where he received his M.D. in 1933. He was a resident in the Stanford University Hospital until 1936. During the summer of 1931, Snoke served as a park ranger in Mount Rainier National Park. While at Stanford, Snoke became acquainted with Parnie Storey, a fellow medical student and the daughter of Parnie and Thomas Storey, the latter being the general director of the school of hygiene and physical education at Stanford. They were married in 1934.

Snoke's residency had been in pediatrics, and he went to the Strong Memorial Hospital, in Rochester, New York, expecting to continue in this field of medicine. In 1937, however, he was offered the position of assistant director of the hospital, under Basil MacLean. Snoke remained in this position through World War II. In 1946, he was asked to become the director of the newly formed Grace-New Haven Hospital. In New Haven, he faced the problems of fusing two medical facilities, their staffs, and budgets, while building a new memorial unit. Snoke was instrumental in balancing the interests and resolving the tensions between the private physicians, who had used the Grace Hospital facilities, and the faculty members of the Yale University Medical School, who had brought their classes to the bedsides of patients in the New Haven Hospital.

Snoke was known for his concern for patient care and for his interest in the role of the university teaching hospital. It was under his influence that the hospital developed the concept of "rooming-in" to allow newborn babies to stay with their mothers in the mother's room. He also developed a training program for hospital administrators and encouraged the improvement of the university's nursing school. Snoke played a major role in the formation of the Yale-New Haven Medical Center, Inc., which raised funds and served as a coordinating structure for the university medical school-hospital partnership.

Snoke was a national leader in hospital administration and was active in professional organizations. He served the American Hospital Association (AHA) in numerous ways, chairing its Councils on Hospital Planning and Plant Operations, on Prepayment Plans and Hospital Reimbursement, and on Professional Practice. He was president of the AHA from 1956-1957 and received the AHA's Distinguished Service Award in 1965. Snoke also served as president of the Connecticut Hospital Association (1954-1955), and was a member of the Joint Commission on Accreditation of Hospitals, the Joint Commission on the Improvement of Care of the Patient and the National Commission on Public General Hospitals. He was often called upon as a consultant on hospital operations and worked in partnership with his wife Parnie, who, besides having an M.D., received a degree in public health from Yale in 1961.

For reasons he did not entirely understand, Snoke was forced to resign as executive director of the Yale-New Haven Hospital on December 31, 1967. He was then named the acting executive director of the Illinois Comprehensive State Planning Agency and Coordinator of Health Services under Governor Richard Ogilvie and held this post until 1973. His resignation followed Ogilvie's defeat for reelection. While in Illinois, he helped develop a model Emergency Medical Service and Trauma Program.

Snoke deplored the tendency of health professionals and health institutions to be preoccupied with the business of medicine rather than the care of patients. He sought ways to bring about cooperation between all types of health care institutions to ensure a continuum of care which would include prevention and post-acute care as well as the treatment of acute illness. Snoke spoke out for a national policy for health and welfare. He was active in the formation of health maintenance organizations and supported the creation of the Medicare system. He was also an advocate of the Connecticut Regional Medical Program. In 1987, the Yale University Press published Snoke's Hospitals, Health, and People , containing his reflections on his long career and such contemporary problems as reimbursement and cost containment, patients' inability to pay for medical care, program management, marketing, and corporate organization. Snoke died on April 18, 1988.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Arranged in five series: I. General Files, 1917-1988. II. Writings, 1937-1988. III. Topical Files, 1937-1982. IV. Personal and Family Papers, 1861-1988. V. Photographs, 1907-1988.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The General Files comprise the largest series in the papers. The series includes correspondence, memoranda, notes, agendas, and minutes which document Albert Snoke's professional interests in health care and hospital administration. The General Files also highlight many of Albert Snoke's personal friendships and civic interests, including a life-long interest in the Boy Scouts and service on the board of the Carrier Corporation. The files are arranged by individual or organizational name in alphabetical order. Within each file the materials are arranged chronologically.

Though the material in these files dates from 1917 to 1988, the bulk of the material dates from after Snoke's resignation as executive director of the Yale-New Haven Medical Center. The earliest files are those for family members, including Snoke's parents, John Waldo and Helen Snoke, his wife, Parnie Snoke, and her parents, Thomas A. and Parnie Storey. Letters to his parents include descriptions of the Boy Scout jamboree in Denmark, while letters to Parnie describe summers spent at Camp Wig-was-ati in Ontario, Canada, during the early 1940s. Files for mentor Basil MacLean and medical friends George Darling, Jack Masur, and David Rytand are also helpful in following Snoke's career. The files for Grace-New Haven Hospital and for Frederick Wiggin supply some information on Snoke's decision to move to New Haven and the evolution of his administration.

Because Snoke's files as executive director remain in the Yale-New Haven Hospital Records, material in the general files for the period of the late 1940s through the mid 1960s generally concerns Snoke's involvement in professional associations. There are a number of files that document Snoke's work with the American Hospital Association, including his year as president. In addition to the files for the association itself, there are also materials in the files of Edwin Crosby and Alexander McMahon. Snoke's involvement in other professional organizations is recorded in the files for the Commission on Public-General Hospitals, the Connecticut Hospital Association, the Joint Commission on Accreditation of Hospitals, the Medical Administrators Conference, and the Society of Medical Administrators.

In 1968 Snoke was forced to resign from the Yale-New Haven Medical Center. Files which document this difficult period in his career include those for Frederick G. Redlich, Yale University, and the Yale-New Haven Hospital. Snoke's activities in the years following his resignation are well-documented in these files. Numerous files concern Snoke's work in Illinois. Files for Governor Richard Ogilvie contain memoranda and position papers outlining Snoke's duties and his ideas on how health care change should or could be brought about in Illinois. Other important correspondents on the work in Illinois include John Dailey, David Kinzer, and George Lindsley.

During the 1970s Snoke was involved in various health care initiatives in Connecticut. The files for New Haven Health Care, Inc., the Connecticut Regional Medical Program, Henry T. Clark, Lawrence DeNardis, and Edward Morrissey contain discussions of these activities. There are also files for various clients for whom Snoke served as a consultant, such as the Candler General Hospital, the Detroit General Hospital, the Jersey City Medical Center, the Kentucky Commission on Public Higher Education, the Samaritan Health Service, and the University of Louisville Health Sciences Center.

In the late 1970s Snoke became interested in plans for a national health care program, and he hoped that a group of colleagues, including John Thompson and Carleton Chapman of the Commonwealth Fund, could publish on this topic. There are mentions of this interest in the files of numerous friends and acquaintances. Eventually Snoke wrote his own book, Health, Hospitals and People . For additional correspondence on this see the files for James Hague and Edward Tripp.

The files demonstrate Snoke's efforts to stay in contact with former students, such as James Malloy, and many personal friends. Many letters mention planned visits. James L. Collier, Lester Leutweiler, John Manz, Wallace Root, and Burns Roensch were all members of the Boy Scout troop that went to the international Jamboree with Snoke in 1924. As the files document, he maintained a particularly close relationship with them.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Series II is composed of drafts and printed copies of Albert Snoke's writings, which take the form of books, articles, reviews, speeches, and reports. As a consultant to numerous hospitals and medical centers, Snoke was called upon to supply written reports. These are arranged at the beginning of the series under the heading "Consultations." The files here are arranged in chronological order and for an individual consultation the file may include background material and notes as well as drafts and the completed report. A large number of reports concern medical institutions in Connecticut and Illinois. There is also a major report to the Health Sciences Education Committee of the Council on Public Higher Education of the Commonwealth of Kentucky.

Files for writings listed by Snoke in his bibliography, a copy of which may be found in box 48, folder 5, are arranged after the consultations under the heading "Bibliographic items." These files are arranged in numerical order according to Snoke's numbering system. Not all bibliographic items, however, are represented in the papers. The files are basically in chronological order. Snoke has included in his bibliography articles and addresses, as well as some formal reports and memoranda, such as those prepared for the Select Advisory Panel on Human Service Organization of the Connecticut Association for Human Services or for the governor of Illinois.

Files for speeches and writings not included in Snoke's bibliography are arranged under the heading "Non-bibliographic items" in chronological order. The documentation for many of these items is briefer or less formal than those in the bibliography. The files may only contain an outline or notes for a talk or a brief typescript for a book review. Since, however, Snoke's bibliography includes only two titles published after 1975, files for some "non-bibliographic" items are similar to those included on the bibliography. There are extensive materials for Snoke's attempts to write a book on implementing a national health care program in the late 1970s and early 1980s and other materials for his 1987 volume, Hospitals, Health, and People . There are also files for a 1980 history of the Medical Administrators Conference, an oral history for the American Hospital Association, and the outlines and drafts for a second book.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series is composed of files dealing with particular subjects of interest to Snoke during his long career in health care administration. For any particular topic the files may include background material in the form of brochures, pamphlets, reports, and the like (though readily available published materials have been removed from the collection), correspondence, notes, and memoranda.

The series begins with files on health planning which relate to Snoke's general interest in federal legislation dealing with comprehensive state health planning agencies and national health insurance. The series continues with files specifically concerning health planning in Connecticut, which relate to attempts during the late 1960s and 1970s to reorganize the structure of state government. Of particular concern was the regionalization of state medical programs and the adequate protection of human resources. Snoke at this time served on the Select Advisory Panel of the Connecticut Association for Human Services, and material in these files documents the work of the panel.

Material filed under the heading "Hospital Administration" concerns the proper relationship between hospitals and physicians. Professional associations for medical specialists contended that doctors could not be salaried staff of a hospital. Thus for a hospital to have physicians as paid staff amounted to the unethical corporate practice of medicine. Through the 1950s and early 1960s, Snoke was involved in attempts by the American Hospital Association to achieve harmonious relationships with medical specialists and to attempt to define common ground for negotiating financial relationships between hospitals and anesthesiologists, pathologists, and radiologists. The files include position papers and background material, including materials from Snoke's participation in the "Iowa Case," where the issue of corporate practice of medicine was actually brought to trial.

The remaining files in the series date from Snoke's service as coordinator of health services in Illinois. They include information on health planning agencies in different regions around the state as well as on particular issues such as cost containment. Files on a conference on the role of the state in health planning, convened by the governor of Illinois, include a copy of the notebook given to each conference participant and the transcript of the proceedings.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series is composed of papers and memorabilia of several Hamilton, Snoke and Storey family members. The papers have been grouped by family or individual and then arranged alphabetically by type of material. The series includes several types of personal papers of Albert Snoke, such as biographical sketches, articles about him, and travel diaries. There is also a significant quantity of material relating to Parnie Storey Snoke, including her correspondence, research notes, files from her civic activities, and school memorabilia. Filed under various members of the Storey family are several types of material which relate to Palo Alto, California and Stanford University. The oldest material in the series is that for Riley Storey and includes diaries kept by him during his military service in the Civil War.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series is composed of photographs of Albert Snoke, various members of the Snoke and Storey families, friends, and professional acquaintances. Photographs of Snoke and of family members are arranged at the beginning of the series under the heading "Family." These photographs include baby pictures and formal portraits. The "Family" photographs are followed by photographs arranged in chronological order, which show Snoke at various times or at particular events. This grouping includes photographs from Snoke's camping trips on Mount Rainier and other scouting events as well as those from speaking engagements and award ceremonies. Photographs filed under the heading "Groups" include photographs of assemblages of association members, conference participants, and students. Portraits, many of them autographed by Snoke's friends and colleagues, are filed alphabetically under the heading "Individuals" at the end of the series.

Photographs that came to Snoke as enclosures in letters from friends have, generally, been left with their letter of transmittal. Only photographs that portray Snoke have been moved to this series. Additional photographs may be found in Series I, folders 56, 116, 125, 129, 140, 153, 163, 190, 200, 239, 249, 267, 295, 300, 319, 340, 342, 343, 352, 355, 357, 400, 403, 414, 432, and 436. There are also photographs in Series IV, folders 17 and 27.
